# Database Conventions

- Use a typed query layer (Drizzle preferred over Prisma for this project — lighter,
  closer to raw SQL, good fit for a single-table-heavy deals schema). Confirm
  choice before scaffolding migrations if not already decided.
- Core table: `deals`, keyed on the `NormalizedDeal.id` hash. Upsert on ingestion
  (`ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE`) — never insert duplicates per refresh cycle.
- Keep a `deal_history` table (or a `previous_price` column) if/when historical low
  tracking matters — don't overwrite price history silently.
- Filtering (price under €10, store, discount %) happens in SQL via query params,
  not fetched-then-filtered in JS — this is a small dataset now but design the
  queries as if it weren't.
- Index on `(price_eur)`, `(normalized_title)`, and `(steam_app_id)` at minimum
  once the table's live — `steam_app_id` is the enrichment lookup key.
- Migrations are explicit files, checked in — no relying on `db push`/sync-on-boot
  for anything past local dev.
- The `deals` table's columns mirror `NormalizedDeal` exactly — no
  `description`/`genres`/`screenshots`/`rating`/etc columns, ever. If a migration
  adds a column like that, it's wrong; game metadata comes from IGDB at render
  time (`060-enrichment.mdc`), not from a database column.

## `source_health` table

Backs the `/status` dashboard (`070-implementation-plan.mdc`). One row per
source, written only by `recordSourceRun()` in `src/lib/db/source-health.ts`,
called from every cron route after every run:

```typescript
interface SourceHealthRow {
  source: string;               // primary key, matches DealSource
  status: 'ok' | 'degraded' | 'broken';
  lastRunAt: string;
  lastSuccessAt: string | null;
  lastFailureAt: string | null;
  lastError: string | null;
  consecutiveFailures: number;
  dealsIngestedLastRun: number | null;
}
```

Upsert on every run (`ON CONFLICT (source) DO UPDATE`) — this table always has
exactly one row per source, never a history table. If historical failure
patterns matter later, that's a separate `source_health_events` table, not this
one.
